Maggie here! Pediatric occupational therapist and mama to two babes. Question — did the phrase “vertical surface” get stuck in your head when I mentioned it five times in a row? I hope so bc it’s key!

Any work on a vertical surface (a wall, window, fridge, etc) is going to build strength in the core and extensor muscles along the back which help with upright posture. It will also provide stability and strength in the upper body which is needed for building fine motor skills in the hands.

Pediatric occupational therapist and mama to two babes here to remind you that little ones learn through repetition. Once your babe is crawling or mobile, starting repeating the simple phrase “feet first” as you simultaneously help them turn around and get down from any surface. It will click and once they’re walking and climbing more and more, you’ll realize how vital it is for them not to go face first off of everything 😅

You may see your little one get confused turning their body around and going the wrong direction with their feet but just let them (*safely) work through it as this is all part of learning the motor plan needed for this skill! 

…also this is vital as an escape route when your big sister realizes you’re in her bed trying to take her stuffies 😅

Pediatric Occupational Therapist + mama to two littles here, HI! 👋🏼 

This is my little dude - he’s sweet, sensitive, wild, but also very cautious and wary of new textures. It took him 6 full days to step in sand on our beach trip and still refuses to walk in grass barefoot. 

Here to tell you from a professional standpoint that THATS OKAY while also giving simple ideas for how to help your little get accustomed to new textures. 

1️⃣ Never force or trick your little into touching something they don’t want to touch. If they tell you no, honor it. Tricking them will only break trust and make it worse.

2️⃣ Try to combine preferred with non preferred. For my little man, the paw patrol toys and water are preferred. The bubbles were the non preferred “challenge” with the activity. 

3️⃣ Give it time. You may end up doing the same activity several days in a row before your little engages fully or at all. Let them set the pace, your job is just to give them the opportunity. 

4️⃣ Set your activity up somewhere you don’t care about being messy. It’s summer, do it outside! 

5️⃣ If simple tips like these aren’t working and you think your little may need more help because being aversive to textures is impacting daily life, talk to your pediatrician and ask for a referral to a pediatric OT. This reel doesn’t count 😉
